Beast Realtime Voice System v0.1

Design doc

1. Purpose

Beast voice is a realtime spoken command system built on Beast principles:
	•	speech becomes visible structure
	•	short commands stay fast and local
	•	long commands become drafted CDI
	•	every step is logged
	•	costly or destructive actions are hard to trigger by accident
	•	a child should be able to use it without breaking the machine

The system should feel immediate, but never reckless.

⸻

2. Core law

Speech is not execution. Speech is draft.

Some commands are safe enough to run instantly. Most are not.

So Beast voice has three modes:

Safe instant

Tiny, obvious, reversible commands.

Examples:
	•	stop
	•	undo
	•	next
	•	zoom in
	•	open gallery
	•	play
	•	pause
	•	show CDI

Guided draft

Multi-step or parameterized intent becomes a visible plan.

Examples:
	•	make a short green goblin on a gray background
	•	search my notes for wan22 latent ideas
	•	reduce this to six colors
	•	build a looping dialogue scene and show me the plan

Protected

Destructive, expensive, or external actions require explicit approval.

Examples:
	•	delete artifacts
	•	overwrite outputs
	•	publish
	•	send
	•	bulk edits
	•	long render jobs

⸻

3. User goal

A user should be able to say something messy like:

Beast, make a goblin sprite on a gray background and reduce it to six colors, but show me the CDI first

And Beast should respond with:
	•	a live draft
	•	a visual plan
	•	optional CDI view
	•	no hidden execution
	•	clear confirmation before compute starts

⸻

4. High-level architecture

voice audio
-> transcript
-> short command parser
-> route decision
-> optional local lookup
-> optional llm draft prompt
-> draft cdi
-> ui preview
-> user approval or refinement
-> approved cdi
-> execution
-> result artifacts + logs

Each step produces an artifact.

⸻

5. System components

5.1 Voice capture

Captures microphone input and chunks it for streaming transcription.

Output artifact:
	•	voice_audio

5.2 Speech-to-text

Produces a streaming transcript with confidence.

Output artifact:
	•	voice_transcript

Fields:
	•	text
	•	timestamps
	•	confidence
	•	partial/final state

5.3 Short command parser

Pure C. No LLM.

Purpose:
	•	detect tiny common commands
	•	extract obvious arguments
	•	execute immediately when safe

Output artifact:
	•	command_parse

Fields:
	•	matched_command
	•	confidence
	•	args
	•	safe_instant yes/no

5.4 Route decision

Decides whether command goes to:
	•	pure C fast path
	•	draft path

Output artifact:
	•	route_decision

Values:
	•	pure_c
	•	llm_draft_required

5.5 Local lookup

Looks up grounded local context before any LLM call.

Sources may include:
	•	current UI state
	•	selected artifact
	•	generator library
	•	command docs
	•	local encyclopedia / belief DB
	•	current model / current tool availability
	•	recent logs

Output artifact:
	•	lookup_context

5.6 LLM draft prompt builder

Builds the exact prompt for the drafting model.

It should include:
	•	transcript
	•	route reason
	•	relevant local lookup results
	•	current app state
	•	CDI syntax rules
	•	instruction to output valid CDI only

Output artifact:
	•	llm_draft_prompt

5.7 CDI drafter

Local LLM drafts strict CDI.

Output artifact:
	•	draft_cdi

5.8 UI preview renderer

Shows the drafted system in a top-to-bottom UI equivalent.

Output:
	•	preview_state

Views:
	•	visual plan
	•	CDI view

5.9 Approval gate

Turns draft into executable intent.

Output:
	•	approved_cdi

5.10 Executor

Runs the approved CDI.

Outputs:
	•	execution logs
	•	result artifacts
	•	lineage metadata

⸻

6. The two-lane model

Lane A: Pure C fast path

For short, obvious commands.

Examples:
	•	stop
	•	undo
	•	open gallery
	•	next image
	•	zoom in
	•	show CDI
	•	search goblin

Properties:
	•	immediate
	•	deterministic
	•	low latency
	•	no LLM cost
	•	no drafting unless confidence is low

Flow:

voice -> transcript -> c parser -> execute

Lane B: Drafted CDI path

For longer or more complex commands.

Examples:
	•	make a short green goblin on a gray background
	•	search my local notes for wan22 and summarize the best findings
	•	build a looping pixel art walk cycle and show me the plan

Flow:

voice -> transcript -> route -> lookup -> llm draft -> preview -> approve -> execute


⸻

7. Realtime UX behavior

7.1 Streaming transcript

Beast shows what it hears as the user speaks.

Example:

I heard:
make a short green goblin…

7.2 Streaming plan

As soon as enough intent is known, Beast starts drafting visible steps.

User says:

make a short green goblin

UI begins showing:
	1.	Generate character

Then user continues:

on a gray background

UI updates:
	1.	Generate character
	2.	Add gray background

Then:

reduce it to six colors

UI updates:
	1.	Generate character
	2.	Add gray background
	3.	Reduce palette to 6 colors

This feels realtime, but stays inspectable.

7.3 Early safe execution

If a command is clearly a safe fast-path command, execute immediately.

User:

stop

Beast stops at once.

7.4 Ambiguity handling

If intent is unclear, Beast drafts instead of pretending certainty.

Example:

make it better

Beast shows:
	•	sharpen image
	•	improve prompt
	•	choose stronger colors

and asks for clarification or keeps listening.

⸻

8. Child-safe design laws

Law 1

No irreversible action from voice alone.

Law 2

All costly actions show a visible plan first.

Law 3

Undo and stop must always be immediate and reliable.

Law 4

Ambiguity lowers the system into draft mode, not action mode.

Law 5

The target of a destructive action must be visible before approval.

Law 6

The system should explain itself in plain language.

Good:
	•	I drafted three steps.
	•	This will erase 14 images.
	•	I’m not sure which one you mean.
	•	Say "run" or "show CDI."

Bad:
	•	Executing optimized multimodal action graph.
	•	Autonomous intent inference complete.

⸻

9. Approval model

9.1 Auto-run allowed

Only for:
	•	safe
	•	reversible
	•	obvious
	•	cheap

9.2 Soft approval

For medium-risk actions.

Example:

I drafted two steps. Say "run" to continue.

9.3 Hard approval

For destructive, expensive, or external actions.

Example:

This will delete 23 artifacts.
Delete them?

Or:

This render may take about 18 minutes.
Start now?

⸻

10. UI design

The UI should mirror CDI structure from top to bottom.

If CDI is:

$$$generate-sprite
$$prompt
$char
short green goblin

$background
on a gray featureless background

$$$reduce-palette
$$tool
$colors
