16. Standard generator library for voice system

These should exist as standard system generators, even if some are implemented in C and some with models.

transcribe-voice

Audio → transcript

parse-short-command

Transcript → route / args

lookup-command-context

Transcript + app state → grounded context

draft-cdi

Transcript + context → CDI

render-preview

CDI → visual plan

approve-cdi

Preview → approved CDI

execute-cdi

Approved CDI → outputs

These are conceptual generators even if the implementation differs.

⸻

17. Safety strategy

17.1 The LLM drafts, it does not execute

The drafting model should output CDI, not click around the app.

This keeps the system bounded.

17.2 Local grounding first

The LLM should never draft from transcript alone if local lookup could clarify available tools or current selection.

17.3 Protected verbs

Special handling for words like:
	•	delete
	•	erase
	•	publish
	•	send
	•	overwrite
	•	spend
	•	wipe
	•	reset

These automatically elevate approval requirements.

17.4 Duplicate compute warning

If the user is about to rerun a known equivalent CDI, Beast warns but allows it.

Example:

This looks like duplicate compute.
Run anyway?

That fits your developer workflow exactly.

⸻

18. Failure model

A good Beast voice system should fail like this:
	•	"I’m not sure what you meant."
	•	"I drafted a plan. Please check it."
	•	"I found two possible targets."
	•	"This action is protected."

It should not fail like this:
	•	silent destructive action
	•	hidden hallucinated execution
	•	no visible interpretation
	•	no undo path

⸻

19. Performance goals

Fast path

Short commands should feel immediate.

Draft path

Long commands should begin rendering a draft quickly, ideally before the user fully finishes speaking.

Logging

Logging must not block interactivity.

Local-first

Short command parsing and as much routing logic as possible should stay in C and local state.

⸻

20. Design motto

Hear clearly. Draft visibly. Run carefully.

⸻

21. One-line definition

Beast Realtime Voice System v0.1 converts spoken intent into visible, inspectable, and reproducible action plans, using pure C for short commands and drafted CDI for complex ones.

