Step 3: extract center point

For each detection:

x_center = (x1 + x2) / 2
y_center = (y1 + y2) / 2

This is your target location in image space

⸻

5. Second milestone: move arm manually

Before connecting vision → movement:

Step 4: control arm directly

Using serial commands or SDK:

move_to(x, y, z)
grip_open()
grip_close()

Test:
	•	move to known positions
	•	open/close gripper

⸻

6. Third milestone: coordinate mapping

This is the hardest part.

Problem

Camera sees:

(x_pixel, y_pixel)

Arm needs:

(x_world, y_world, z_world)


⸻

Solution (v0.1 simple)

Manual calibration

Pick 3–4 points:
	1.	Place object at known arm positions
	2.	record:
	•	pixel coordinates
	•	arm coordinates

Then compute simple mapping:

x_world = a * x_pixel + b
y_world = c * y_pixel + d

You can start with linear mapping.

Not perfect, but works for small area.

⸻

7. Fourth milestone: pick and place

Basic sequence

detect object
→ map to world coords
→ move above object
→ lower
→ close gripper
→ lift
→ move to target
→ open gripper


⸻

Example pseudo-code

target = detect_object()

x, y = pixel_to_world(target)

move_to(x, y, z_high)
move_to(x, y, z_low)

grip_close()

move_to(x, y, z_high)
move_to(target_x2, target_y2, z_high)

move_to(target_x2, target_y2, z_low)

grip_open()


⸻

8. Fifth milestone: verification loop

After action:

capture frame
detect again
compare expected vs actual

If wrong:
	•	retry
	•	adjust

This is where Beast shines.

