5. Design Principles

5.1 Generators are small

Each generator does one thing well.

Avoid:
	•	giant "do everything" vision models

Prefer:
	•	composable steps

⸻

5.2 Explicit artifacts

No hidden state.

Every step:
	•	takes input
	•	produces output
	•	logs result

⸻

5.3 Replaceability

Any generator can be swapped:
	•	YOLO → another detector
	•	SAM → another segmenter
	•	simple mapping → learned mapping

No pipeline rewrite needed.

⸻

5.4 Observability

Every intermediate result can be:
	•	visualized
	•	inspected
	•	replayed

⸻

5.5 Closed-loop ready

VGL is designed to support:

perceive → act → perceive → verify

Even if CDI remains linear, higher-level systems can loop.

⸻

6. Minimal Hardware Binding

VGL assumes:
	•	fixed camera
	•	known coordinate mapping
	•	stable lighting

Hardware abstraction occurs in:
	•	capture-frame
	•	execute-arm

Everything else is hardware-agnostic.

⸻

7. Execution Guarantees

VGL generators must:
	•	produce deterministic outputs where possible
	•	or log enough data for reproducibility
	•	avoid hidden randomness
	•	expose model + config

⸻

8. Error Handling

Each generator should output:

{
  "success": true,
  "error": null
}

or

{
  "success": false,
  "error": "no objects detected"
}

Pipelines should not silently fail.

⸻

9. v0.1 Limitations
	•	no multi-camera fusion
	•	no advanced SLAM
	•	no dynamic scene understanding
	•	no learned grasping
	•	no collision avoidance

Focus is:

simple, visible, debuggable systems

